ğŸ¯ Distance Metrics for Music Recommendations
To recommend similar songs, I tested two widely used distance metrics:

ğŸ“Œ Euclidean Distance (Straight-Line Similarity)
âœ… Measures absolute distance in feature space.
âœ… Works well in low-dimensional data.
âŒ Sensitive to scale differences (e.g., loudness variations can skew results).
âŒ Not ideal for high-dimensional data like music features.

ğŸ“Œ Cosine Similarity (Pattern-Based Similarity)
âœ… Measures the angle between feature vectors instead of absolute difference.
âœ… Ignores differences in scale, focusing on song patterns.
âœ… Works well for high-dimensional data, making it ideal for music recommendations.
âœ… Used in real-world systems like Spotify, Netflix, and YouTube.

ğŸš€ Key Takeaway?
Cosine Similarity outperformed Euclidean Distance for song recommendations because it focuses on feature patterns rather than raw numerical values. This ensures better recommendations even if two songs have different loudness or tempo ranges.

